    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3314874785" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3314874785" />
    <a title="Debbie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41918078-debbie"><img alt="Debbie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1594390250p2/41918078.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3314874785?book_show_action=true">Aug 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Debbie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Debbie" href="/user/show/41918078-debbie">Debbie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audiobook 9781508266488" href="/book/show/39829104-the-library-book">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Lovers of libraries!</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=informative">informative</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=2020-reads">2020-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=american-west-coast">american-west-coast</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=audiobook">audiobook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=books-about-books">books-about-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3314874785" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7723254906819480381">An enjoyable and informative account about libraries in general, and specifically, of the 1986 fire of the Los Angeles Public Library. So many things that I liked about THE LIBRARY BOOK include:<br/>1. each chapter begins with a small list of titles and call numbers of books pertaining to that chapter;<br/>2. the intense step-by-step vivid description of the fire&apos;s progression throughout the library;<br/>3. history of well-known libraries, but especially this particular library, including its architecture, pas</span>
  <span id="freeText7723254906819480381" style="display:none">An enjoyable and informative account about libraries in general, and specifically, of the 1986 fire of the Los Angeles Public Library. So many things that I liked about THE LIBRARY BOOK include:<br />1. each chapter begins with a small list of titles and call numbers of books pertaining to that chapter;<br />2. the intense step-by-step vivid description of the fire's progression throughout the library;<br />3. history of well-known libraries, but especially this particular library, including its architecture, past and present librarians, its contents, its patrons (one was even a serial killer!); <br />4. the demise of libraries and of books, even how and why books go missing;<br />5. how books are "cleaned" (including after being handled by patrons with contagious diseases - so pertinent today!) as well as how damaged books are restored;<br />6. how books were delivered in the past and how they continue to be delivered to this day;<br />7. the role the Internet plays in reviving a strong interest in libraries (I enjoyed the section about Overdrive); and<br />8. extensive information about the alleged arsonist, or even if arson was the cause of this fire.<br /><br />One tiny issue for me was the voice of the narrator (who happens to be the author) seemed to be monotone at first, but I grew to enjoy listening to her story as it progressed.<br /><br />Overall, a fascinating (and even a horror) story for librarians and library/book lovers alike! Susan Orlean's story shows how libraries are an integral part of society, which led me to develop an enlightened appreciation for librarians and the behind-the-scenes of all libraries. A must-read for library lovers!</span>
  <a data-text-id="7723254906819480381" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


